<subSubSection pageId="10" pageNumber="529" type="disussion">
<paragraph blockId="10.[1988,2582,2094,2521]" pageId="10" pageNumber="529">
This species was classified as ajunior synonym of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Peters" baseAuthorityYear="1874" box="[2095,2235,2252,2285]" class="Mammalia" family="Pseudocheiridae" genus="Pseudochirops" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diprotodontia" pageId="10" pageNumber="529" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="albertisii">P. albertisii</taxonomicName>
, but it was recognized as a distinct species in the 1990s. Monotypic.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="10" pageNumber="529" type="distribution">
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6670524" ID-Zenodo-Dep="6670524" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6670524/files/figure.png" inLine="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="529" targetBox="[1374,1965,2104,2517]" targetPageId="10">
<paragraph blockId="10.[1988,2582,2094,2521]" pageId="10" pageNumber="529">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1988,2161,2330,2363]" pageId="10" pageNumber="529">Distribution.</emphasis>
NW New Guinea, Arfak Mis in the Bird's Head (= Vogelkop) Peninsula.
</paragraph>
</caption>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="10" pageNumber="529" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="10.[1988,2582,2094,2521]" lastBlockId="10.[1375,2582,2528,3113]" pageId="10" pageNumber="529">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1989,2242,2409,2442]" pageId="10" pageNumber="529">Descriptive notes.</emphasis>
Head-body 34-35 cm, tail 28-33 cm; weight 1-5 kg. The Reclusive Ring-tailed Possum differs from D’Albertis’s Ring-tailed Possum (
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Peters" baseAuthorityYear="1874" box="[1848,2000,2528,2561]" class="Mammalia" family="Pseudocheiridae" genus="Pseudochirops" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diprotodontia" pageId="10" pageNumber="529" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="albertisii">P. albertisii</taxonomicName>
), which it superficially resembles, by being 50% larger and having softer and longer fur, short hairs near tips of ears, darker gray underfur, and larger cheek teeth. It differs from the Coppery Ring-tailed Possum (
<taxonomicName authorityName="Thomas" authorityYear="1897" box="[1390,1520,2646,2679]" class="Mammalia" family="Pseudocheiridae" genus="Pseudochirops" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diprotodontia" pageId="10" pageNumber="529" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="cupreus">P. cupreus</taxonomicName>
) in having longer fur on at least one-half ofits tail.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="10" pageNumber="529" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="10.[1375,2582,2528,3113]" pageId="10" pageNumber="529">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1377,1488,2685,2718]" pageId="10" pageNumber="529">Habitat.</emphasis>
Apparently only primary forest in areas that are remote from villages. The Reclusive Ring-tailed Possum has been recorded at elevations of 1000-2250 m.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
